{"id":"2204.06104","submitter":"Bassam Bamieh","authors":"Bassam Bamieh","title":"A Tutorial on Solution Properties of State Space Models of Dynamical\n  Systems","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"eess.SY cs.SY math.DS math.FA math.OC","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/","abstract":"  The starting point of analysis of state space models is investigating\nexistence, uniqueness and solution properties such as the semigroup property,\nand various formulas for the solutions. Several concepts such as the state\ntransition matrix, the matrix exponential, the variations of constants formula\n(the Cauchy formula), the Peano-Baker series, and the Picard iteration are used\nto characterize solutions. In this note, a tutorial treatment is given where\nall of these concepts are shown to be various manifestations of a single\nabstract method, namely solving equations using an operator Neumann series\ninvolving the Volterra operator of forward integration. The matrix exponential,\nthe Peano-Baker series, the Picard iteration, and the Cauchy formula can be\n\"discovered\" naturally from this Neumann series. The convergence of the series\nand iterations is a consequence of the key property of asymptotic nilpotence of\nthe Volterra operator. This property is an asymptotic version of the nilpotence\nproperty of a strictly-lower-triangular matrix.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 12 Apr 2022 22:20:09 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 16 Apr 2022 16:41:29 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sun, 24 Apr 2022 17:15:17 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-04-26"}
